Lesson 3: introduction to Models and the Admin

# create a model in models.py for example:

class mymodel(models.Models):
  text = models.CharField(max_length=30)
  number = models.IntegerField()
  
  
A ist of Django model data types (e.g. Charfield, DecimalField) can be found here: https://www.webforefront.com/django/modeldatatypesandvalidation.html

# always run migrations in the terminal after changing models.py. 
python3 manage.py makemigrations
python3 manage.py migrate


# After creating the model you need to register it in the admin.py file

from .models import mymodel

admin.site.register(mymodel)

# This will make your model visible in the django admin
